Trigger Warning ‼️🚨

I was hesitant to post this out of fear it may bring me back to a place where the majority of my PTSD resides; however, I feel as if not sharing my story would be more selfish, as opposed to having high hopes that I can help many, and perhaps save a life or two by sharing my trauma for the better. 

It’s been four years this month that I almost lost my life from the result of senseless acts of domestic violence; a toxic relationship that I did not know how to exit.  What I once thought was love; ended in a choke hold, strangulation, extreme beatings, head trauma, and a fight for a breath that I was sure would be my last. 

I have read & heard of one too many stories lately of which ended by victims not having the opportunity to seize a second chance at life. I decided to share a few of the less graphic photos on here to cast a glimpse inside the depths of domestic violence, and my personal experience that took me to the darkest of places. For anyone out there feeling trapped, scared, confused, manipulated - please know you are not alone. There are an abundance of resources out there to help get you to the other side. I promise it does get better; you are loved & you will find the respect you deserve and a hand to hold with someone who will take great care of you. 

Often times, these agonizing experiences can leave us feeling alone, broken, and worst of all, hopeless. These pictures remind me that I am so much more worthy than a moment in time I once let define me.  Remember, healing is a marathon, not a sprint. We must stand together and shine a light on a subject matter that does not receive the signifance of attention it should. Don’t give up on love, and most importantly, don’t give up on yourself. Be patient and be forgiving of yourself. Love yourself first, and I promise, you will attract that same energy in return. ❤️🙏🏼#itgetsbetter
